The image below shows the Voigt Model for viscoelastic materials, along with the displacement time plot obtained after the instantaneous application of a unit force,

$$F$$, which is later instantaneously removed.


In this system a spring (with spring constant $$k$$) is connected in parallel with a dashpot (with fluid of viscosity $$\eta$$).




From the initial application of load, up until equilibrium has been established, this model is characterised by the following equation:


$$u=\frac{F}{k}\left(1-e^{\left(-\frac{k.t}{\eta }\right)}\right)$$


where $$u$$ is the displacement in the system as a function of time, $$t$$.


A controlled study of a Voigt model is set up, in which $$F=k=\eta$$.

In this study, $$F$$ is applied at time $$t=0$$.


Part A

What is the displacement in the system when $$t=1.8$$?

(Please give your answer accurate to 3.d.p., and carry forward this level of accuracy should any values be required in later calculations)

Part B

Suppose that before equilibrium is reached (at a time, $$T=6$$, and a displacement $$\underline{U}$$, say) the unit force, $$F$$, on the Voigt model is instantaneously removed.

Which of the equations below correctly describes the subsequent displacement, $$u\left(t>T\right)$$, as a function of time, $$t$$.

Part C

What is the value of $$\underline{U}$$ in this case?

(Please give your answer accurate to 3.d.p.)

{1:NUMERICAL:=0.998:0.0005#Good Job!!~*#Incorrect}

Part D

What is the value of $$t$$ when the displacement of the system returns to the value of $$u$$ calculated in Part A?

generalfeedback.text:
Parts A&C

Due to the equivalence of the parameters given in the question, the equation for initial displacement (for when $$t

$$u=1-e^{-t}$$


Part B

The equation for subsequent displacement (for when $$t>T$$), is governed by a relationship of exponential decay, starting at the point $$\left(T,\underline{U}\right)$$, and gradually returning to zero over a period of time determined by the strength of the spring and the viscosity of the fluid in the dashpot.

The correct answer is therefore as shown, and in the case of this question, it can be further simplified to:

$$u\left(t>T\right)=\underline{U}\cdot e^{\left(T-t\right)}$$


Part D

To solve this part, first of all the equation for Part B needs to be rearranged to give:

$$t=-\left(\ln \left(\frac{u}{\underline{U}}\right)-T\right)$$

You will then need to input the value of $$T$$ given in the question, and your values of $$u$$ and $$\underline{U}$$ as calculated in the earlier parts of the question.
